# App Queries Pattern (Queries + Entity)

When adding data-access queries in `app/src/queries`, use this structure:

- Create one `*Entity.ts` file that exports only the entity type used by the app.
- Create one `*Queries.ts` file that exports a `namespace <Domain>Queries`.
- Keep one query concern per domain folder (for example `queries/level`).

## Entity rules

- Name the type `<Domain>Entity` (example: `LevelEntity`).
- Include only fields returned by the API and needed by the app.
- Keep it as a TypeScript `type` (no runtime logic).

## Queries rules

- Namespace name must be `<Domain>Queries` (example: `LevelQueries`).
- Query methods should be explicit (`getAll`, `getById`, `create`, etc.).
- Use app fetch resources (`Instance.engine.getResource(Fetch)`).
- Use `apiAuth` for authenticated routes and `api` for public routes.
- Type all responses with the matching `*Entity` type.

## Imports and exports

- Do not use `index.ts` barrels in `app/src/queries/*`.
- Import directly from concrete files:
  - `queries/<domain>/<Domain>Entity`
  - `queries/<domain>/<Domain>Queries`

## Example (level)

```ts
// queries/level/LevelEntity.ts
export type LevelEntity = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  serialized: string;
};
```

```ts
// queries/level/LevelQueries.ts
import { Instance } from "../../Instance";
import { Fetch } from "../../resources/fetch/Fetch";
import type { LevelEntity } from "./LevelEntity";

export namespace LevelQueries {
  export function getAll() {
    const fetch = Instance.engine.getResource(Fetch);
    return fetch.apiAuth.get<LevelEntity[]>("/level");
  }
}
```
